And it's the first, your
second, and your third course.

00:50:29.940 --> 00:50:31.740
So it's three courses in one.

00:50:31.740 --> 00:50:32.584
That was one.

00:50:32.584 --> 00:50:34.000
Who would be at
the table would be

00:50:34.000 --> 00:50:36.280
my grandpa and my wife, my son.

00:50:36.280 --> 00:50:38.370
That would probably be--
my parents, of course.

00:50:38.370 --> 00:50:40.060
My grandpa-- I'd
grown up on the farm.

00:50:40.060 --> 00:50:42.960
My grandpa is a big
part of my life.

00:50:42.960 --> 00:50:45.350
Of course, I haven't
seen him forever.

00:50:45.350 --> 00:50:46.520
He's long gone now.

00:50:46.520 --> 00:50:47.150
That's why.

00:50:47.150 --> 00:50:51.440
But I had a pretty awesome--
there was another question of,

00:50:51.440 --> 00:50:54.800
what was your best day
of eating in your life?

00:50:54.800 --> 00:50:57.990
One was recently in New York.

00:50:57.990 --> 00:50:59.870
If you ever follow
me on Facebook,

00:50:59.870 --> 00:51:01.630
I had a marathon of eating.

00:51:01.630 --> 00:51:02.860
I had 20-something pizzas.

00:51:02.860 --> 00:51:04.870
I had to go to old
friends, new guys.

00:51:04.870 --> 00:51:07.330
And I was a mess.

00:51:07.330 --> 00:51:09.097
But I had to see--
sometimes, you've

00:51:09.097 --> 00:51:10.430
just got to see what's going on.

00:51:10.430 --> 00:51:12.304
It's been a while since
I really had a chance

00:51:12.304 --> 00:51:13.690
to do that in New York.

00:51:13.690 --> 00:51:15.420
Sometimes, you're checking
on what you're doing, just

00:51:15.420 --> 00:51:17.128
to see-- make sure
you're doing it right.

00:51:17.128 --> 00:51:19.990
It's always cool to
double-check it and see it.

00:51:19.990 --> 00:51:23.290
And there was one day that
I was eating a cannoli

00:51:23.290 --> 00:51:25.860
on Mulberry St.,
walking in the rain.

00:51:25.860 --> 00:51:28.360
And I was saying, I
was like John Travolta

00:51:28.360 --> 00:51:31.450
eating his cannoli, after I
had seven pizzas that morning.

00:51:31.450 --> 00:51:33.704
And it was one of those days
that you had to have-- I

00:51:33.704 --> 00:51:35.620
was at Roberta's that
day, Prince Street Pizza

00:51:35.620 --> 00:51:37.150
out of Soho Square.

00:51:37.150 --> 00:51:39.830
I had all these pieces that
day that were really great.

00:51:39.830 --> 00:51:43.470
That was a great day for me.

00:51:43.470 --> 00:51:45.830
Another time, we went to
Italy, and my wife and I

00:51:45.830 --> 00:51:46.540
were traveling.

00:51:46.540 --> 00:51:47.960
And I got lost.

00:51:47.960 --> 00:51:54.490
I stumbled onto some place
that I could never find again.

00:51:54.490 --> 00:51:56.580
All of a sudden,
this town appeared.

00:51:56.580 --> 00:51:58.224
And we went to this
restaurant, and it

00:51:58.224 --> 00:52:00.390
was a four-star restaurant
in the middle of nowhere.

00:52:00.390 --> 00:52:02.290
I don't even get how
they would even do that,

00:52:02.290 --> 00:52:04.090
but it was one of our
best meals we ever had.

00:52:04.090 --> 00:52:06.180
I had a Florentine steak
that came to your table.

00:52:06.180 --> 00:52:10.019
And it was just a rare that went
to medium-rare on the table,

00:52:10.019 --> 00:52:11.060
and it was just sizzling.

00:52:11.060 --> 00:52:12.740
And everything came,
and it was cool.

00:52:12.740 --> 00:52:16.240
It was one of those moments that
was unexpected, but beautiful

00:52:16.240 --> 00:52:17.130
at the same time.

00:52:17.130 --> 00:52:17.800
Yeah?

00:52:17.800 --> 00:52:21.515
AUDIENCE: Is there hope for
the mass-market pizza industry?

00:52:21.515 --> 00:52:23.265
TONY GEMIGNANI: Meaning
like frozen lines?

00:52:23.265 --> 00:52:25.400
AUDIENCE: Or frozen
or improvements?

00:52:25.400 --> 00:52:26.700
TONY GEMIGNANI: I think
there's a lot of improvement.

00:52:26.700 --> 00:52:28.074
I've worked on
some frozen lines,

00:52:28.074 --> 00:52:30.315
actually, for three years.

00:52:30.315 --> 00:52:31.690
Everybody's doing
the same thing.

00:52:31.690 --> 00:52:33.530
Why is frozen pizza
always the same?

00:52:33.530 --> 00:52:34.900
It's horrible.

00:52:34.900 --> 00:52:38.130
Well, there's only a few places
that really manufacture it.

00:52:38.130 --> 00:52:41.141
And when you manufacture it
on a big level on a line,

00:52:41.141 --> 00:52:42.890
It's hard to change
anything on that line.

00:52:42.890 --> 00:52:45.560
It's a 24/7 line,
that everybody's

00:52:45.560 --> 00:52:48.210
making these same pizzas,
because the lines are all

00:52:48.210 --> 00:52:48.816
the same.

00:52:48.816 --> 00:52:50.940
It's important to find a
warehouse or somebody that

00:52:50.940 --> 00:52:52.960
could have a line
that can adapt or can

00:52:52.960 --> 00:52:54.950
add this or do this and do that.

00:52:54.950 --> 00:52:58.780
And that's what will make a
pizza different and better

00:52:58.780 --> 00:53:01.240
than those.

00:53:01.240 --> 00:53:03.820
Preservatives-- there's a
lot of extra excess in dough

00:53:03.820 --> 00:53:04.840
that I hate.

00:53:04.840 --> 00:53:07.642
When it comes to frozen pizza,
I hate dough conditioners.

00:53:07.642 --> 00:53:09.600
There's one thing that,
if you look on the box,

00:53:09.600 --> 00:53:10.970
there's a dough
conditioner on the dough,

00:53:10.970 --> 00:53:12.650
or L-cysteine, and
stuff like that.

00:53:12.650 --> 00:53:13.550
I can't stand it.

00:53:13.550 --> 00:53:17.520
And you're able to make a
great frozen line without that.

00:53:17.520 --> 00:53:20.480
So maybe you'll
see Tony's Pizza.

00:53:20.480 --> 00:53:22.480
Well, not Tony's-- there's
already Tony's Pizza.

00:53:22.480 --> 00:53:23.938
You've got to think
Tony G's Pizza.

00:53:23.938 --> 00:53:26.100
We have a frozen line
coming out, pretty good.

